******
[1] Senegal: top priority emergency (WHO)
Date: 30 Aug 2014
Source: WHO Epidemiology and surveillance [edited]
http://www.who.int/csr/don/don_updates/en


On 30 Aug 2014, Senegal's Ministry of Public Health and Social Affairs provided WHO with details about a case of Ebola virus disease (EVD) announced in that country on 29 Aug 2014. WHO has also received details of the emergency investigation immediately launched by the Government. Testing and confirmation of EVD were undertaken by a laboratory at the Institut Pasteur in Dakar [capital of Senegal].

The case is a 21-year-old male native of Guinea who arrived in Dakar by road on 20 Aug 2014 and stayed with relatives at a home in the outskirts of the city. On 23 Aug 2014, he sought medical care for symptoms that included fever, diarrhoea, and vomiting. He received treatment for malaria, but did not improve and left the facility. After leaving the facility, he continued to reside with his relatives. Though the investigation is in its early stages, he is not presently known to have travelled elsewhere. On 26 Aug 2014, he was referred to a specialized facility for infectious diseases, still showing the same symptoms, and was hospitalized. On 27 Aug 2014, authorities in Conakry, Guinea issued an alert informing medical services in Guinea and neighbouring countries that a person who was a close contact of a confirmed EVD patient had escaped the surveillance system. That alert prompted testing at the Dakar laboratory, launching an investigation and triggering urgent contact tracing.

Health sector response
-------------------
WHO is treating this 1st case in Senegal as a top priority emergency. Key operational personnel were dispatched to Dakar [30 Aug 2014]; others will follow. The Government of Senegal has informed WHO of the urgent need for epidemiological support, personal protective equipment, and hygiene kits. These needs will be met with the fastest possible speed.

