[3] Prevention & suspect cases

Nigeria: contacts
----------------
31 Aug 2014: (PressTV) Some 160 people have been placed under medical surveillance over the deadly Ebola virus [disease] in the Nigerian city of Port Harcourt in Rivers State. "As of today [31 Aug 2014], none of them has shown symptoms of any kind. We are in touch with them constantly, and they also call us to tell us their condition," Sampson Parker, the health commissioner of Rivers State, said on Fri [29 Aug 2014]. The people who are being monitored had been in contact with a doctor who died from the virus. The Nigerian government said on Thursday [28 Aug 2014] that the doctor, Ikyke Samuel Enuemo, was the country's 6th person to die from the disease. http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2014/08/29/377028/nigeria-monitors-160-people-over-ebola

Spain (Malaga) ex Nigeria
---------------------
31 Aug 2014: Malaga Regional Hospital has activated its EVD protocol after the arrival at 5:30 a.m. of a 40-year-old man with symptoms of the virus. The patient, of Nigerian origin and a resident of Antequera, returned on 17 Aug 2014 from a journey to his homeland; he presented with a very high fever at the moment of his admission.

These circumstances obliged the Andalusian Health Service to activate its EVD protocol and immediately admit the patient. He is now in isolation in the infectious-cases unit of the 5th floor of Carlos Haya Hospital. He is in a room designed for his condition and is being cared for by professionals "prepared and equipped for it," according to sources in the Regional Hospital.

The patient arrived in the morning at the Carlos de Haya Regional Hospital, having come from Antequera to Malaga. Although an ambulance was ready to transport him, he used his own vehicle to make the trip to the capital. He arrived accompanied by his wife and 2 [other] children, who had no symptoms and could return home [to their holiday apartment].

The entire family recently returned from a trip to Nigeria, where, according to WHO, the virus has spread with force recently. "At the moment, this is only a suspected case, but since he has been in a danger zone recently, we feel obliged to treat the case as if he were infected with EVD," hospital sources said. http://www.laopiniondemalaga.es/malaga/2014/08/31/paciente-padecer-ebola-varon-nigeriano/703738.html [in Spanish, trans. by Crawford Kilian.
See map at http://www.antequerarural.com/images/mapa_grande.jpg. - Mod.JW]

Sweden ex West Africa
-------------
31 Aug 2014: (ITV) A possible case of EVD is being investigated by a hospital in Sweden, local media has reported. A man who recently travelled to a "risk area" was being treated in an isolation unit at the Karolinska University Hospital in Stockholm, the reports said. They added that doctors are currently running tests on the man, who recently returned from West Africa where the disease has claimed [over] 1500 lives.
http://www.itv.com/news/story/2014-08-31/possible-ebola-case-investigated-in-sweden

WHO helps Gambia prevent EVD
-------------------------------
30 Aug 2014: (Xinhua) The World Health Organization (WHO) has equipped the Gambian Ministry of Health and Social Welfare with laboratory materials to combat the deadly EVD, Gambia's officials said on Sat [30 Aug 2014]. "We are supporting the government through its ministry to close ranks against the deadly EVD, which is spreading in West Africa," said Charles Saego Moses, a WHO country Representative in Gambia. The materials were handed over to the ministry through the ministry deputy permanent secretary Dawda Ceesay, who noted that Gambia should not be complacent despite [the fact] that no EVD case has been detected in the country. ... The ministry has increased surveillance teams at the border to ensure the health check of those going out of and coming into Gambia, Ceesay said. According to the WHO, more than 3000 people have been infected with EVD. On Fri [29 Aug 2014], Senegal, Gambia's neighboring country, confirmed its 1st case of EVD, making it the 5th West African country to be affected by the outbreak.
http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/world/2014-08/31/c_133609045.htm

[Gambia is an English-speaking country completely surrounded by French-speaking Senegal; see map: http://geology.com/world/the-gambia-map.gif. - Mod.JW]

